# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1902-chicago-white-stockings-season
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The **1900 major league baseball season** began on April 19, 1900.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The regular season ended on October 14, with the Brooklyn Superbas as the regular season champion of the National League.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The Superbas and runner-up Pittsburgh Pirates competed in the *Chronicle-Telegraph* Cup, a precursor to the current World Series, over four days, with Game 1 on October 15 and ended with Game 4 on October 18.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The Superbas defeated the Pirates in the best-of-five series in four games.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The 1900 season saw the return of a postseason championship series (albeit as a one-off), the *Chronicle-Telegraph* Cup, following the end of the Temple Cup in 1897.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The 1900 season saw the aftermath of the National League contracting from 12 to 8 teams, eliminating the Baltimore Orioles, Cleveland Spiders, Louisville Colonels, and Washington Senators.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The elimination of major-league baseball from these cities prompted the minor league American League to declare themselves as a major league the following year.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The 1900 schedule consisted of 140 games for the eight teams of the National League.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] Each team was scheduled to play 20 games against the other seven teams in the league.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] This format had previously been used by the National League during their 1888–1891 seasons.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] This format would last until 1904, which saw an increase of games played.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] Opening Day took place on April 19 featuring all eight teams.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The final day of the season on October 14.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] The *Chronicle-Telegraph* Cup, a precursor to the current World Series, took place between October 15 and October 18.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1900-major-league-baseball-season] 15 tie games, which are not factored into winning percentage or games behind (and were often replayed again), occurred throughout the season.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1901 Chicago White Stockings season** was their first season as a major league team, and their second season in Chicago.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] It was also the inaugural season of American League as a major league.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Stockings had a very balanced lineup, which was led by outfielders Dummy Hoy and Fielder Jones, and scored the most runs in the AL.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] They relied primarily on speed, as Frank Isbell, Sam Mertes, and Jones finished 1–2–3 in stolen bases.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1901-chicago-white-stockings-season] The pitching staff was anchored by Clark Griffith, who went 24–7 with a 2.67 ERA.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The 1902 Baltimore Orioles season finished with the Orioles in 8th place in the American League (AL) with a record of 50–88.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The team was managed by John McGraw and Wilbert Robinson.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The team played at Oriole Park in Baltimore, Maryland.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] During the season, Andrew Freedman, principal owner of the National League's (NL) New York Giants, with the financial backing of John T.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Brush, principal owner of the NL's Cincinnati Reds, purchased the Orioles from John Mahon, who was deeply in debt.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] They raided the Orioles roster, releasing several of Baltimore's better players so that they could sign them to the Giants and Reds.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] AL president Ban Johnson seized control of the Orioles the next day and restocked their roster with players received on loan from other AL teams.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The Orioles' second season in Baltimore would ultimately prove to be their last, as after the season the team was replaced by the New York Highlanders, now known as the New York Yankees.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Knowing that placing a franchise in New York City was key to the success of the American League (AL), AL president Ban Johnson secretly met with principal owner John Mahon and player-manager John McGraw, who was also a part-owner, before the season about relocating to New York.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] However, the transfer did not occur when they could not find a suitable venue for the team.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] In March, Mike Donlin went on a drinking binge in Baltimore, during which he was arrested for urinating in public and assaulting two chorus girls.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The Orioles released Donlin when he was sentenced to six months in prison.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Notable players jumped to the Orioles from the rival National League (NL).
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] In December 1901, Joe Kelley jumped from the Brooklyn Superbas.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Later in the offseason, Jimmy Sheckard also jumped from Brooklyn.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Kip Selbach and Jim Jackson jumped from the New York Giants, Ernie Courtney jumped from the Boston Beaneaters, Tom Hughes jumped from the Chicago Orphans, and Dan McGann jumped from the St.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The Orioles signed Bill Keister as a free agent.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] With these transactions, the Orioles were seen as a contender in the AL pennant going into the 1902 season.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The Orioles drew over 10,000 fans on Opening Day.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Three players returned to the NL in April 1902.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Jack Dunn and Steve Brodie jumped to the Giants in April.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Sheckard changed his mind about playing for the Orioles after four games, returning to Brooklyn.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Many Orioles found themselves suspended by Johnson by midseason, including McGraw and Kelley.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] In early July, McGraw resigned from the team and signed with the New York Giants of the NL.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] At this point, the Orioles had a 26–31 record.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Kelley and Wilbert Robinson succeeded McGraw as player-managers.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The franchise began to fall into significant debt by July.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Kelley, son-in-law of part-owner John Mahon, reported that the team owed as much as $12,000 ($446,538 in current dollar terms).
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Unable to afford that debt, Mahon purchased shares of the team from Kelley and McGraw.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] With this, Mahon became the majority shareholder, owning 201 of the team's 400 shares.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] On July 17, 1902, Mahon sold his interest in the Orioles to Andrew Freedman, principal owner of the Giants, and John T.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Brush, principal owner of the Cincinnati Reds, also of the NL.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The transaction was reported to have been in the range of $20,000 ($744,231 in current dollar terms).
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] That day, Freedman and Brush released Kelley, Joe McGinnity, Roger Bresnahan, Jack Cronin, Cy Seymour, and Dan McGann from their Oriole contracts.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Brush then signed Kelley and Seymour to the Reds, while Freedman signed McGinnity, Bresnahan, Cronin, and McGann, joining McGraw, his new player-manager, on the Giants.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Though Kip Selbach and Jimmy Williams were both pressed to agree to relocate as well, they refused to leave Baltimore, saying they would honor their two-year contracts.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] McGinnity allegedly attempted to contact Johnson that night, offering to stay with the Orioles if he could receive Johnson's personal assurance that he was welcome to stay.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] McGinnity did not hear back from Johnson, who had left his phone off the hook that night to avoid being contacted, and joined his teammates with the Giants.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] On that day, the Orioles were forced to forfeit their game against the St.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Louis Browns, as Baltimore lacked the minimum number of players required to compete.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Johnson used a league rule to join the Orioles' minority owners to seize control of the team.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Now running the Orioles, Johnson sought to restock the team.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] He requested players from the other AL franchises to fill the Orioles' roster.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Sport McAllister was loaned to the Orioles from the Detroit Tigers for three games, but the Tigers requested McAllister back, as the Orioles came to Detroit to play the Tigers.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The Orioles received Pop Dillon from the Tigers, but released him after using him in two games.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Snake Wiltse was sent to the Orioles from the Philadelphia Athletics on July 19, but he struggled for the Orioles.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The Orioles also received Lew Drill on loan from the Washington Senators, sold Charlie Shields to the St.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] Louis Browns and purchased Jack Thoney from the Cleveland Bronchos.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] The Orioles finished the season with a 50–88 record, good for last place in the AL.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] For their final game at Oriole Park, the team drew only 138 fans.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] During the owners meetings in late 1902, the franchise was transferred to New York.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-baltimore-orioles-season] MLB would not return to Baltimore until the former Browns moved to Baltimore in 1954.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The **1902 Boston Americans season** was the second season for the professional baseball franchise that later became known as the Boston Red Sox.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The Americans finished third in the American League (AL) with a record of 77 wins and 60 losses, 6+1⁄2 games behind the Philadelphia Athletics.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The team was managed by Jimmy Collins and played its home games at Huntington Avenue Grounds.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The Americans bolstered their pitching by recruiting Bill Dinneen, who jumped from the Boston Beaneaters.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-boston-americans-season] Dinneen and Cy Young would become the "one-two" pitching combination for the Boston Americans.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-boston-americans-season] Prior to the regular season, the team held spring training in Augusta, Georgia.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The offense was led by Buck Freeman, who hit 11 home runs and had 121 RBIs, and Patsy Dougherty with a .342 batting average.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The pitching staff was led by Cy Young, who made 45 appearances (43 starts) and pitched 41 complete games with a 32–11 record and 2.15 ERA, while striking out 160 in 384+2⁄3 innings.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-boston-americans-season] The team had one game end in a tie; August 18 vs.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-boston-americans-season] Tie games are not counted in league standings, but player statistics during tie games are counted.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-boston-beaneaters-season] The **1902 Boston Beaneaters season** was the 32nd season of the franchise.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-brooklyn-superbas-season] The **1902 Brooklyn Superbas** finished in a distant second place in the National League, 27.5 games behind the Pittsburgh Pirates.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-chicago-orphans-season] The **1902 Chicago Orphans season** was the 31st season of the Chicago Orphans franchise, the 27th in the National League (NL), and the tenth at West Side Park.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-chicago-orphans-season] The Orphans finished fifth in the National League with a record of 68–69–6 (.496 winning percentage).
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-chicago-white-stockings-season] The **1902 Chicago White Stockings season** was a season in American baseball.
[src:1902-chicago-white-stockings-season/1902-chicago-white-stockings-season] The White Sox had a record of 74–60, finishing in fourth place in the American League.
